    "narrative": "Our offensive projections for April 7th prioritize aggressive targeting of favorable park factors and high-ceiling matchups against middling starters. **Mickey Moniak (75.75)** and **James Wood (73.10)** headline our daily outlook; Moniak benefits from a massive 14% park boost, while Wood\u2019s prime leadoff spot against a sub-optimal Matthew Liberatore maximizes his plate appearance potential in a favorable platoon-neutral environment. **Vinnie Pasquantino (71.09)** remains a core start, as his 14% dynamic platoon edge against the right-handed G. Williams outweighs the slight negative impact of incoming wind. **Corbin Carroll (61.21)** presents an intriguing tactical play; while facing a stiff test in Freddy Peralta, his 4% boost for speed-dependent scenarios\u2014leveraging the likelihood of swiping bags against slower pitcher delivery\u2014is the exact type of profile Ghost Ride the WHIP leans into to navigate the scarcity of our 5x5 SB category.\n\nBench decisions were largely dictated by lineup uncertainty and negative platoon splits, with **Jose Caballero (47.69)** serving as the hardest exclusion. While Caballero\u2019s sprint speed usually mandates a start, his 13% dynamic platoon penalty against Aaron Civale and a suboptimal #8 batting position dropped him just below the threshold for our MI/UTIL slots, where we opted for the higher-floor reliability of Zach McKinstry and Trevor Story. Managers should exercise caution regarding the \"Lineup Pending\" status across the board; the wind-in warnings at multiple venues, specifically affecting Moreno, Carroll, and Stanton, have suppressed their base scores. Monitor the confirmed lineups closely, as the 5%\u20139% drag from adverse wind could render some of these marginal starters (sub-50 scores) risky plays if the projected batting order slips further down the lineup.",
